Discussion of plots

On the plots above we can see a relation between age and the insurance costs, the older we get the more expensive it gets. We can also see that insurance costs are generally higher for smokers vs non-smokers.

Furthermore, we can see that bmi doesnât impact non smokers a lot as it seems to be pretty flat, but for smokers, the higher the bmi, the higher the charges.

On the last plot we can guess sex most likely doesnât really play a role in insurance costs as we see no clear difference between the males and females. We can further analyze sex and region by having a boxplot of them to see if there are any clear differences.

Part Two: Simple Linear Models

1. Construct a simple linear model to predict the insurance charges from the beneficiaryâs age. Discuss the model fit, and interpret the coefficient estimates.

from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, OneHotEncoder, PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score, mean_squared_error
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.preprocessing import FunctionTransformer
## splitting x_train and X_test for the only time
X = health_insur.drop('charges', axis=1)
y = health_insur['charges']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.25)

def return_same(X):
  return X

pass_variable = FunctionTransformer(return_same)
# creating collum tranformer to use only variable age
ct = ColumnTransformer(
  [('untouched_exp_var', pass_variable, ['age'])
  ],
  remainder = "drop"
)

#creating pipeline
lr_pipe = Pipeline(
    [('preprocessing', ct),
        ('linear_reg', LinearRegression())]
)

#fitting it
fitted_lr_pipe = lr_pipe.fit(X_train,y_train)


y_preds = fitted_lr_pipe.predict(X_test)

r2_part11 = r2_score(y_test, y_preds)
mse_part11 = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_preds)

coeff = fitted_lr_pipe.named_steps['linear_reg'].coef_

r2_part11, mse_part11, coeff
(0.11288430494799195, 140116956.47691017, array([214.60773371]))

if we are trying to predict the insurance costs based on age, we dont get a very good result as we can see our r squared of only .11.

The coefficient of the explanatory age tells us that for one year increase in age, the predicted insurance cost will increase by 214.61 dollars.

Now when we add soke, we see that our model performed a lot better. This is represented by the new r squared of .739. We can conclude that whether you are a smoker or not probably plays a huge role in determining your insurance costs

For each model, fit the model on the original data.

Then, use the fitted model to predict on the new data.

Report the MSE for each modelâs new predictions. Based on this, which is the best model to use?

Make a plot showing the residuals of your final chosen model.

new_insur = pd.read_csv("https://www.dropbox.com/s/sky86agc4s8c6qe/insurance_costs_2.csv?dl=1")
Xnew = new_insur.drop('charges', axis=1)
ynew = new_insur['charges']

Model 3 - age, bmi and smoker as predictors

ct = ColumnTransformer(
  [('untouched_exp_var', pass_variable, ['age','bmi']),
   ("dummify", OneHotEncoder(), ['smoker'])
  ],
  remainder = "drop"
)

lr_pipe = Pipeline(
    [('preprocessing', ct),
        ('linear_reg', LinearRegression())]

r2_part33 = r2_score(ynew, y_preds)
mse_part33 = mean_squared_error(ynew, y_preds)

Model 4 - age and bmi with both interaction with smoker


ct_dummies = ColumnTransformer(
  [("dummify", OneHotEncoder(sparse_output = False), ["smoker"])],
  remainder = "passthrough"
).set_output(transform = "pandas")


ct = ColumnTransformer(
  [('untouched_exp_var', pass_variable, ['remainder__age','remainder__bmi']),
   ("interaction", PolynomialFeatures(interaction_only = True), ["remainder__age", "dummify__smoker_yes"]),
   ("interaction2", PolynomialFeatures(interaction_only = True), ["remainder__bmi", "dummify__smoker_yes"])
  ],
  remainder = "drop"
)

#creating pipeline
lr_pipe = Pipeline(
    [('preprocessing1', ct_dummies),
     ('preprocessing2', ct),
        ('linear_reg', LinearRegression())]
)


fitted_lr_pipe = lr_pipe.fit(X,y)


y_preds4 = fitted_lr_pipe.predict(Xnew)

r2_part34 = r2_score(ynew, y_preds4)
mse_part34 = mean_squared_error(ynew, y_preds4)

Model 5 - age, bmi, smoker and both quantitative variables interacting with smoker

Part Five: Full Exploration

Using any variables in this dataset, and any polynomial of those variables, find the model that best predicts on the new data after being fit on the original data.

Make a plot showing the residuals of your final chosen model.

ct_dummies = ColumnTransformer(
  [("dummify", OneHotEncoder(sparse_output = False), ["smoker"])],
  remainder = "passthrough"
).set_output(transform = "pandas")


ct = ColumnTransformer(
  [('untouched_exp_var', pass_variable, ['remainder__bmi','dummify__smoker_yes']),
   ("interaction2", PolynomialFeatures(interaction_only = True), ["remainder__bmi", "dummify__smoker_yes"]),
   ('polynmial3', PolynomialFeatures((1,3)), ['remainder__age'])
  ],
  remainder = "drop"
)

#creating pipeline
lr_pipe = Pipeline(
    [('preprocessing1', ct_dummies),
     ('preprocessing2', ct),
        ('linear_reg', LinearRegression())]
)


fitted_lr_pipe = lr_pipe.fit(X,y)


y_preds_final = fitted_lr_pipe.predict(Xnew)

r2 = r2_score(ynew, y_preds_final)
mse = mean_squared_error(ynew, y_preds_final)

r2, mse
(0.8614425035775972, 21483316.779372808)
residuals_final = ynew - y_preds_final

residuals_final_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Predicted': y_preds_final,
    'Residuals': residuals_final
})


residual_plot = (
